	                    Online bullying - don't play the game


	                    <span id="Template_ctl08_lblMessage"><font color="Red"></font></span>

	                </h1>
                	
<p><a onclick="window.open(this.href, '_blank'); return false;" href="http://ceop.police.uk/" onkeypress="if (event.keyCode==13) {window.open(this.href, '_blank'); return false;}"><img width="304" alt="Clenched fist coming through a computer monitor, representing cyber-bullying" class="BorderImageRight" title="Clenched fist coming through a computer monitor, representing cyber-bullying" src="/images/cyberbully2.jpg" height="260"/></a>Between
23 April and 4 May 2012 the Safer Neighbourhood Team, based at
Leith Police Station, will be leading a series of&nbsp;Internet
Safety events at primary schools in the Leith area.<br />
<br />
They&nbsp;will be directed towards Primary 6 and Primary 7 classes
with the focus being on cyberbullying. As a result it will be given
the title &lsquo;Online Bullying - Don&rsquo;t Play The Game.&rsquo;<br />
<br />
The presentation will make use of material developed by the Child
Exploitation and Online Protection Centre (CEOP) and involve whole
class discussion, group work and drama.<br />
<br />
The legacy of the event will be a poster competition centred on the
issue of cyberbullying, and the overall winner will have their
poster printed up and distributed throughout the Leith area in
locations such as libraries, Police Stations and other public
buildings.<br /></p>
<table summary="Box">
<tbody>
<tr>
<td><img width="21" alt="Link" title="Link" src="/images/link_icon.jpg" height="21"/></td>
<td><a onclick="window.open(this.href, '_blank'); return false;" href="http://ceop.police.uk/" onkeypress="if (event.keyCode==13) {window.open(this.href, '_blank'); return false;}">Child Exploitation and Online Protection
(CEOP) website</a></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Schools are also being offered the opportunity to have a
presentation given to parents. This will focus on raising awareness
and the basic principles of keeping their children safe
online.<br />
<br />
<span>As part of the campaign, school pupils will be asked to
design a poster on the issue of cyber-bullying. The winning poster
will then be exhibited in public buildings throughout Leith,
including police stations, libraries and community centres.<br />
<br />
Sergeant Colin Johnston said: "Social networking and online
communication has become increasingly popular with the younger
members of our communities and it is essential that children are
provided with all the necessary advice and information for staying
safe while online.<br />
<br />
"This campaign is focussed on education so that internet users can
identify the types of behaviour that constitutes cyber-bullying and
avoid committing these offences.<br />
<br />
"We also hope that, as a result of our engagement with schools,
anyone who observes cyber-bullying or believes they are currently
victim to it will come forward and report the matter to
police."</span></p>
